{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611017"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:07:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:07:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16197"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16197"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.03,0.09,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8888"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1891"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10651"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESuccessful breastfeeding requires proper mechanical function of infant oral structures and coordinated reflexes. Various anatomical and functional factors can interfere with effective milk transfer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanical factor that impairs effective breastfeeding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cleft palate","Maternal anxiety","Insufficient milk production","Poor let-down reflex","Infant jaundice"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecleft palate\u003C/strong\u003E is a significant mechanical barrier to successful breastfeeding. The defect in the roof of the mouth prevents the infant from creating adequate negative pressure needed for effective sucking and milk transfer. This anatomical abnormality directly interferes with the mechanics of breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal anxiety\u003C/strong\u003E can affect the let-down reflex but is not a mechanical factor. \u003Cstrong\u003EInsufficient milk production\u003C/strong\u003E is a supply issue rather than a mechanical problem. \u003Cstrong\u003EPoor let-down reflex\u003C/strong\u003E relates to hormonal function rather than mechanics. \u003Cstrong\u003EInfant jaundice\u003C/strong\u003E may cause lethargy and poor feeding but is not a mechanical impediment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther mechanical factors that can affect breastfeeding include tongue-tie, micrognathia, and facial nerve palsy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cleft palate impairs the ability to generate negative pressure required for effective sucking during breastfeeding.","Mechanical factors affecting breastfeeding include anatomical abnormalities of the infant\u0027s oral cavity and facial structures.","Successful breastfeeding requires coordinated sucking, swallowing, and breathing."],"references":["Pang J, Broyles J, Redett R. Cleft lip and palate. Eplasty. 2013;13:ic25. Epub 2013 Jan 30. PMID: 23409216; PMCID: PMC3567612.","Reilly S, Reid J, Skeat J, Cahir P, Mei C, Bunik M; Academy of Breastfeeding Medicine. ABM clinical protocol #18: guidelines for breastfeeding infants with cleft lip, cleft palate, or cleft lip and palate, revised 2013. Breastfeed Med. 2013 Aug;8(4):349-53. doi: 10.1089/bfm.2013.9988. Erratum in: Breastfeed Med. 2013 Dec;8(6):519. PMID: 23886478; PMCID: PMC3725852.","Kosowski TR, Weathers WM, Wolfswinkel EM, Ridgway EB. Cleft palate. Semin Plast Surg. 2012 Nov;26(4):164-9. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1333883. PMID: 24179449; PMCID: PMC3706041.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16197"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:00:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:01:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8888"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a juni